Mod specific logs can be found here (This is an opt-in feature for Nucleus compatible mods). The logs are separated into client side logs and server logs avaible for server admins only. By default, max. number of logs that is loaded and can be searched is 400 (2 log files). To load more files, click on the the logs options button found in the top right corenr of the Logs View.

LStrings.DE: Lösche alte Server-Logs um die Ladezeiten zu verbessern.

Clear logs older than X days:
LStrings.DE: Lösche Logs älter als X Tage:

LStrings.EN: The minimum value is 7 days to ensure that there is always an adequate number of logs in case of issues.
LStrings.DE: Der Mindestwert liegt bei 7 Tagen um sicher zu stellen, dass im Falle eines Problems genug Logs zur Verfügung stehen.

LStrings.EN: Amount of log files to be loaded into the game (Logs View)
LStrings.DE: Anzahl der Logdateien, die in das Spiel geladen werden sollen (Logs Ansicht)

LStrings.EN: Be careful with using bigger number as it may result in server lag whenever you open the Logs View as it needs to send all the log data to your client (may disconnect you).
To big of a number may result in short game freezes when opening the Logs View.
The log system is one of the optional systems that a mod can integrate with and offer a much easier overview of things happening in the back and help debug when something goes wrong.
The system can handle large amount of logs without impacting the stability of a server or client by splitting logs in multiple files (200 logs per file).

Logs by default are stored in "/Saved/SaveGames/SESSION_NAME/ServerOrClient/MOD_NAME/Logs/x.sav" where each x.sav contains up to 200 log items, and by default, only the last two files are loaded into the memory and are displayed in the Logs View.
In case of an issue with a Nucleus compatible mod, it is safe to send this log files to the mod author to help them in understanding what may have happened to produce such issue.
Server logs are stored on the server and are not visible to normal players as they may contain data that's only for the eyes of an Admin.
Client logs are stored on the players own pc and are only available to them.
LStrings.DE: Client-Logs werden nur auf dem PC des Spielers gespeichert und sind nur für diesen verfügbar.

The dino catalog can be used to learn more about the dinos on a Server, be it vanilla dinos or modded, we got them all. Use the 3D preview to see how a dino would look like with different color combinations and if you have the permissions spawn such a dino on to the map or change some global settings for them if availible.

Modded Dinos shows ONLY Dinos inclueded by the selected mod. To view all availible dinos (Modded & Vanilla), access the Dino Catalog found in the "Server Info" Pages Section if not disabled by your Server Admin(s).
The dino catalog can be used to discover all the dinos in the game, used or hidden unfinished dinos.
If using the catalog inisde the "Mod Hub", only dinos added by the currently selected mod ar shown.
If a dino has settings that can be changed using Nucleus, a new "Settings" button will appear beside the"Spawn" button.

The item catalog can be used to learn more about the items on a Server, be it vanilla items or modded, we got them all. Use the 3D preview to see how a item looks like with different color combinations and if you have the permissions spawn such a item to your inventory or change some global settings for them if availible.

Modded Items shows ONLY Items inclueded by the selected mod. To view all availible items (Modded & Vanilla), access the Items Catalog found in the "Server Info" Pages Section if not disabled by your Server Admin(s).
The item catalog can be used to discover all the items in the game, used or hidden unfinished items.
If using the catalog inisde the "Mod Hub", only items added by the currently selected mod ar shown.
If a item has settings that can be changed using Nucleus, a new "Settings" button will appear beside the"Spawn" button.

Mod specific localization strings can be found here (This is an opt-in feature for Nucleus compatible mods). The localization strings are provided by the mod dev or auto generated if an unknown string passes trough the translation layer and is made available for users to translate. You can import localization or share your own custom translation with others. Translations of the same mod are shared across all servers and single player sessions you play.

Use this generated string to share your custom translation with others or to generate an empty translation template that can be sent to someone for translation.
The localization system is one of the optional systems that a mod can integrate with and make the mod more accessible to non-english speaking players.
A mod can provide translations to as many languages as they want or just provide the native language and leave it to players to translate it to their languages and share translations with each other.
Even if a translation is provided by the mod dev, users can still add custom translations for that language if they are not satisfied with th provided translation.

In case that a mod author used a string for which they didn't provide any translation, an auto entry will be generated at the moment that string is displayed somewhere and will be available for translation. If the player has the localization view open at that time, a refresh will be needed for the auto entry to appear in the list.
IMPORTANT: Localization saves are not bound to a session, which means, a translation of a mod will be shared by all server you play one and your single player session.
WARNING: This will remove the custom translation for all languages related to this item.
Removing all custom translations for an unused auto generated entry will make sure it doesn't get saved anymore and with that will disappear from the list after a game restart.
As localization is shared between sessions, removing a custom translation here will remove it for all servers you play on as well as your single player session.

Mod specific settings can be found here (This is an opt-in feature for Nucleus compatible mods). The settings are split in Server Wide Settings (only accessible to the Master Admin), Server Player Setting and Client Player Settings(stored localy on their pc, usefull for toggling UI elements and other features that don't affect other players).
The configuration system allows mods to expose their settings to be managed by the Nucleus UI and make them more accessible and easy to chang at runtime.

1.) Server Wide Settings - Managed by the Master Admin and poeple that were given access to it. This settings are stored on the server and are mostly used for global server wide settings (settings that normaly go in the .ini config file).

2.) Server Player Settings - Managed by the Player in question,Master Admin and poeple that were given access to it. This settings are stored on the server as well but are unique to each player. This are the player settings that could affect other players or some server side logic. (An example would be toggling of visual elements on the character that can be seend by other players as well).

3.) Client Player Settings - Managed by the Player in question only. This settings are stored on the players PC and are not accessible to the server if not manualy replicated. This are the player settings that affect only the player in question and have no impact on other players or the server. (An example would be toggling of UI elements that are only visible to the player).
